A structure and a union are both user-defined data types in C used to store different types of data under one name.

A structure stores each member in a separate memory location. This means all the variables inside a structure can hold values at the same time. It uses more memory because each member gets its own space. Structures are commonly used for storing records like student or employee data.

A union, on the other hand, stores all members in the same memory location. This means only one member can hold a value at a time. When a new value is assigned to a different member, the previous value is overwritten. Unions use less memory because all members share the same space.

In simple terms, structures are used when we need to store and use all values together, while unions are used when we want to save memory and only need one value at a time.
